    <section id="faq">
        <h2>Rules FAQ</h2>
        <p>Last updated: September 24, 2025</p>
  
        <div class="faq-grid">
          <details>
            <summary>How do I know if a meld card is legal?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                We only look at the front face. The back is ignored when 
                considering Mana Value, Color Identity, or other restrictions.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>How does Partner / Background work?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                As long as both cards meet deckbuilding restrictions, you 
                can use them. If you play with more than one commander, you 
                start the game with a forced mulligan.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>Can I change my Commander between games/matches?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                No. Your configuration is locked at the start of the event. 
                You can swap cards between your 49 and sideboard, but the 
                Commander(s) never change.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>Can I use cards with X in the casting cost?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Yes. We look at the mana value with X=0. If the card has 
                MV 3 or less with X=0, it is legal.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>Can I use Adventure cards?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                <strong>Discrete Philosophy Check:</strong> Every part of the 
                card must be MV 3 or less. You must check the creature 
                AND the Adventure spell. If either part is MV 4+, the 
                entire card is illegal.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>How do I determine Mana Value of MDFCs?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                <strong>Discrete Philosophy Check:</strong> For Modal Double-Faced 
                Cards, both sides must, independent of the other, meet the MV 3 
                restriction and the color identity of your Commander(s).
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>How many colors can I play?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                There is no limit aside from your Commander's identity. 
                If you find a legal 5-color Commander, you can play 5 colors.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>Can I use a Companion?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Yes. Your companion and your deck/commander(s) must 
                all meet the Companion's restrictions and the TSMCR.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>Can I use Split Cards (such as Fire//Ice)?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                <strong>Discrete Philosophy Check:</strong> Split cards are 
                evaluated by checking each half independently. All halves 
                must have a mana value of 3 or less for the card to be legal.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>How do I determine Color Identity?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Identity includes all colors in the Mana Cost, Rules Text, 
                and Color Indicators. For double-faced cards, always 
                check the back side (except for Meld cards).
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>How do I know if I can use a flip card?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                We only look at the "default" (unflipped) characteristics. 
                The flipped state is ignored for legality.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>Does having multiple Commanders affect my hand?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Yes. If you have more than one, you take a forced mulligan 
                at the start of the game.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>Can I use digital-only or Alchemy cards?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                No. TLR is a paper format. All cards use their Oracle 
                text found on Gatherer.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>How does the forced mulligan work?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Draw an opening seven, then put one on the bottom of your 
                library. This counts as your first mulligan.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>Can I use Serum Powder on the forced mulligan?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                No. Since the first mulligan is forced and involves no 
                choice, Serum Powder cannot replace it. It can apply 
                to future mulligans.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
    
          <details>
            <summary>How does Urza's Bauble work?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Looking at a card is a one-sided reveal. Your hand remains 
                your hand. In a physical game, looking at a card with an 
                opponent is essentially looking at it together.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* Local Styles for FAQ Interactions */
  
  .contact-box {
    background: var(--surface); /* Fixed: removed hardcoded transparency */
    padding: 1rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
    border-left: 4px solid var(--accent); /* Fixed: corrected var name */
  }

  .download-buttons {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }

  .btn-download {
    background: var(--surface); /* Fixed: adapts to all themes */
    color: var(--heading-color); /* Fixed: ensures text is readable on light/dark */
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle); /* Fixed: removed hardcoded border color */
    transition: border-color 0.2s, transform 0.2s;
  }
  
  .btn-download:hover {
    border-color: var(--accent); /* Highlighting border is safer than guessing a background color */
    transform: translateY(-1px);
  }

  details {
    background: var(--surface); 
    border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
    border-radius: 6px;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  summary {
    padding: 1rem;
    cursor: pointer;
    font-weight: bold;
    color: var(--heading-color);
    list-style: none; 
    transition: background-color 0.2s;
  }
  
  summary:hover {
    /* Using --bg here creates a nice "inset" or "contrast" feel against the surface */
    background-color: var(--bg); 
  }

  summary::marker {
    color: var(--accent); /* Fixed: corrected var name */
  }

  .faq-answer {
    padding: 1rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
    /* Using --bg makes the answer feel "recessed" inside the card */
    background: var(--bg); 
    color: var(--text-body);
  }
</style>